The surface compositions and element valence states of the copper paper was characterized by X-ray photoelectron spectroscopy (XPS) technique. Fig. 3 A clearly reveals the presence of Cu, O and C elements, the peaks of O and C are attributed to the paper cellulose, while the peaks of Cu 2P are generated by the Cu crystals. As exhibited in Fig. 3B, there are two individual peaks at ∼933.9 and ∼932.2 eV belonging to Cu 2p, which is due to the binding energies of CuO and Cu2O, indicating that the surface of CuNPs was impressionable to oxidation, mainly the formation of Cu–Cu2O complex structure. To further investigate the crystalline properties of the composite, X-ray diffraction (XRD) analysis was carried out (Fig. 3C). Apart from the diffraction peaks located at 14.80, 16.49, and 22.78° belonging to the (101), (10
1 ‾
), and (200) planes of semicrystalline cellulose. The diffraction peaks at 43.30, 50.41, and 74.15° (blue line) assigned to the (111), (200), and (220) crystal planes of face-centered cubic crystalline copper (JCPDS 04–0836). In addition, four additional diffraction peaks at 38.18, 44.40, 64.58, and 77.55° of the Au@rGO/PCWE (red line), which could be attributed to the (111), (200), (220), and (311) crystal planes of cubic gold (JCPDS 04–0784). While Fig. 3D shows the Raman spectra of Au@rGO/PCWE, it consists of two characteristic peaks at 1344 and 1591 cm−1 that correspond to the D and G band respectively (Liu et al., 2021). The G band caused by the in-plane vibration of sp2 carbon atom, which is the main characteristic peak of rGO, and D band is due to the vibration of sp3 hybrid C atom, approving that rGO was successfully assembled on the PCWE.
